The above model provides a simple but general biogeochemical system where cellular physiology is coupled to an environment, and can be deployed to address ecosystems of various ecological complexity. First we consider the case where an environment is dominated by a single species, which would correspond to the measurement of a consistent particle size in our framework. Taking the known physiological scaling relationships for extant life (Box 2) we find that the size of the organism has a strong effect on the stoichiometric ratios of both the particles and fluid. Figure 4 gives the steady state N:P of cells as a function of steady state environmental N:P and cell size. The variation in the steady-state environmental and cellular N:P was achieved by varying the inflow concentrations Ri,0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
